1 "§ 18D-301. Licensure and local control.
2 (a) An on-site consumption establishment shall only operate if the local regulatory
3 authority in the locality where it is located issued a permit, license, or registration that expressly
4 allows the operation of the on-site consumption establishment.
5 (b) Except as provided in this subsection, a locality may prohibit the operation of any or
6 all types of cannabis establishments within its jurisdiction through the enactment of an ordinance.
7 A locality's prohibition on cannabis establishments shall not prohibit transportation through the
8 locality or deliveries within the locality by cannabis establishments located in other jurisdictions.
9 (c) A locality may enact ordinances or regulations not in conflict with this Chapter, or
10 with rules enacted pursuant to this Chapter, governing the time, place, manner, and number of
11 cannabis establishment operations. A locality may establish civil penalties for violation of an
12 ordinance or regulations governing the time, place, and manner of a cannabis establishment that
13 may operate in such locality.
14 (d) No locality may negotiate or enter into a host community agreement with a cannabis
15 establishment or a cannabis establishment applicant. As used in this subsection, a "host
16 community agreement" means an agreement that the cannabis establishment or applicant provide
17 monies, donations, in-kind contributions, services, or anything of value to the locality.
18 "Article 4.
19 "Possession and Use of Cannabis.
20 "§ 18D-400. Personal use of cannabis.
21 Notwithstanding any other provision of law, except as otherwise provided in this Chapter,
22 the following acts are not unlawful and shall not be a criminal or civil offense under State law or
23 an ordinance of any locality, or be a basis for seizure or forfeiture of assets under State law, for
24 persons 21 years of age or older:
25 (1) Possessing, consuming, ingesting, smoking, growing, using, processing,
26 purchasing, or transporting an amount of cannabis that does not exceed the
27 possession limit.
28 (2) Transferring an amount of cannabis that does not exceed the possession limit
29 to a person who is 21 years of age or older without remuneration.
30 (3) Controlling property where actions described by this section occur.
31 (4) Assisting another person who is 21 years of age or older in any of the acts
32 described in this section.
33 "§ 18D-401. Restrictions on personal cultivation; penalty.
34 (a) It is unlawful to cultivate cannabis plants in any of the following ways:
35 (1) Cannabis plants may not be cultivated in a location where the plants are
36 subject to public view, including view from another private property, without
37 the use of binoculars, aircraft, or other optical aids.
38 (2) A person who cultivates cannabis must take reasonable precautions to ensure
39 the plants are secure from unauthorized access and access by a person under
40 21 years of age. For purposes of illustration and not limitation, cultivating
41 cannabis in an enclosed, locked space that persons under 21 years of age do
42 not possess a key to constitutes reasonable precautions.
43 (3) Cannabis cultivation may only occur on property lawfully in possession of the
44 cultivator or with the consent of the person in lawful possession of the
45 property.
46 (b) A person who violates subsection (a) of this section is guilty of an infraction,
47 punishable by a fine of up to seven hundred fifty dollars ($750.00) or up to 75 hours of
48 community service.
49 "§ 18D-402. Public smoking prohibited; penalty.
50 (a) It is unlawful to smoke cannabis in a public place.
Page 6 DRH10183-NLf-22

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) It is unlawful to smoke cannabis in an area of an on-site consumption establishment
2 where cannabis smoking is prohibited.
3 (c) A person who violates this section is guilty of an infraction, punishable by a fine of
4 up to fifty dollars ($50.00) or up to five hours of community service.
5 "§ 18D-403. Consuming cannabis while operating a moving vehicle prohibited; penalty.
6 (a) No person shall consume cannabis while operating or driving a motor vehicle, boat,
7 vessel, aircraft, or other motorized device used for transportation.
8 (b) Unless the conduct is covered under some other provision of law providing greater
9 punishment, a person who violates subsection (a) of this section, and only consumed cannabis,
10 is guilty of an infraction, punishable as follows:
11 (1) For a first offense, any or all of the following:
12 a. A fine of not more than two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00).
13 b. Not more than 25 hours of community service.
14 c. Suspension of the person's drivers license for up to six months.
15 (2) For a second or subsequent offense, any or all of the following:
16 a. A fine of not more than five hundred dollars ($500.00).
17 b. Not more than 50 hours of community service.
18 c. Suspension of the person's drivers license for up to one year.
19 "§ 18D-404. False identification; penalty.
20 (a) A person who is under 21 years of age may not present or offer to a cannabis
21 establishment or the cannabis establishment's agent or employee any written or oral evidence of
22 age that is false, fraudulent, or not actually the minor's own for either of the following purposes:
23 (1) Purchasing, attempting to purchase, or otherwise procuring or attempting to
24 procure cannabis.
25 (2) Gaining access to a cannabis establishment.
26 (b) A person who violates this section is guilty of an infraction, punishable by a fine of
27 not more than one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00) or up to 15 hours of community service.
28 "§ 18D-405. Unlawful cannabis extraction; penalty.
29 (a) No person, other than a cannabis product manufacturing facility complying with this
30 Chapter and Department rules, may perform solvent-based extractions on cannabis using solvents
31 other than water, glycerin, propylene glycol, vegetable oil, or food-grade ethanol.
32 (b) No person may extract compounds from cannabis using ethanol in the presence or
33 vicinity of open flame.
34 (c) A person who violates this section is guilty of a Class E felony, which shall include a
35 fine of not more than five thousand dollars ($5,000).
36 "§ 18D-406. Cannabis accessories authorized.
37 (a) Except as provided in this section, notwithstanding any other provision of law, it is
38 not unlawful and shall not be an offense under State law or an ordinance of any locality, or be a
39 basis for seizure or forfeiture of assets under State law, for persons 21 years of age or older to
40 manufacture, possess, possess with intent to distribute, or purchase cannabis accessories or to
41 distribute or sell cannabis accessories to a person who is 21 years of age or older.
42 (b) Except as provided in this section, a person who is 21 years of age or older is
43 authorized to manufacture, possess, and purchase cannabis accessories and to distribute or sell
44 cannabis accessories to a person who is 21 years of age or older. This section is intended to meet
45 the requirements of section 863 of Title 21 of the United States Code by authorizing, under State
46 law, any person in compliance with this Chapter to manufacture, possess, or distribute cannabis
47 accessories.
48 (c) No person may manufacture, distribute, or sell cannabis accessories that violate rules
49 adopted by the Department. A first offense under this section is an infraction, punishable by a
50 fine of up to one thousand dollars ($1,000) and forfeiture of the cannabis accessories. A second
51 or subsequent offense of this section is a Class A1 misdemeanor punishable by a fine of up to
DRH10183-NLf-22 Page 7

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 five thousand dollars ($5,000), up to 180 days in jail, or both, and forfeiture of the cannabis
2 accessories.
3 "§ 18D-407. Purchasing of cannabis or cannabis accessories unlawful in certain cases;
4 penalties; treatment and education programs and services.
5 (a) No person to whom cannabis or cannabis accessories may not lawfully be sold under
6 this Chapter shall consume, purchase, or possess, or attempt to consume, purchase, or possess,
7 any cannabis or cannabis accessories.
8 (b) Any person 18 years of age or older who violates subsection (a) of this section is
9 guilty of an infraction, punishable by a fine of up to twenty-five dollars ($25.00) or up to five
10 hours of community service. Additionally, the person shall be ordered to enter a substance abuse
11 treatment or education program or both, if available, that in the opinion of the court best suits the
12 needs of the person.
13 (c) Any juvenile who violates subsection (a) of this section is guilty of an infraction,
14 punishable by a fine of up to twenty-five dollars ($25.00) or up to five hours of community
15 service. Additionally, the juvenile shall be ordered to enter a substance abuse treatment or
16 education program or both, if available, that in the opinion of the court best suits the needs of the
17 juvenile.
18 "§ 18D-408. Nondiscrimination for personal use of cannabis.
19 (a) A person shall not be subject to arrest, prosecution, or penalty in any manner, or be
20 denied any right or privilege, including, but not limited to, disciplinary action by a business,
21 occupational, or professional licensing board or bureau, solely for conduct permitted under this
22 Chapter.
23 (b) Except as provided in this section, neither the State nor any of its political
24 subdivisions may impose any penalty or deny any benefit or entitlement for conduct permitted
25 under this Chapter or for the presence of cannabinoids or cannabinoid metabolites in the urine,
26 blood, saliva, breath, hair, or other tissue or fluid of a person who is 21 years of age or older.
27 (c) Except as provided in this section, the State nor any of its political subdivisions may
28 deny a drivers license, a professional license, housing assistance, social services, or other benefits
29 based on cannabis use or for the presence of cannabinoids or cannabinoid metabolites in the
30 urine, blood, saliva, breath, hair, or other tissue or fluid of a person who is 21 years of age or
31 older.
32 (d) Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, a person shall not be denied
33 custody of or visitation with a minor for acting in accordance with this Chapter, unless the
34 person's behavior is such that it creates an unreasonable danger to the minor that can be clearly
35 articulated and substantiated.
36 (e) Except as provided in this section, neither the State nor any of its political
37 subdivisions may deny employment or a contract to a person for engaging in conduct permitted
38 under this Chapter for a prior conviction for a nonviolent cannabis offense that does not involve
39 distribution to minors, or for testing positive for the presence of cannabinoids or cannabinoid
40 metabolites in the urine, blood, saliva, breath, hair, or other tissue or fluid of the individual's
41 body.
42 (f) For the purposes of medical care, including organ and tissue transplants, the use of
43 cannabis does not constitute the use of an illicit substance or otherwise disqualify a person from
44 needed medical care and may only be considered with respect to evidence-based clinical criteria.
45 (g) Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, unless there is a specific finding
46 that the individual's use, cultivation, or possession of cannabis could create a danger to the
47 individual or another person, it shall not be a violation of conditions of parole, probation, or
48 pretrial release to do either of the following:
49 (1) Engage in conduct allowed by this Chapter.
50 (2) Test positive for cannabis, delta-9 tetrahydrocannabinol, or any other
51 cannabinoid or metabolite of cannabis.
