7 "§ 18D-411. Occupational licensing.
8 (a) A holder of a professional or occupational license may not be subject to professional
9 discipline for providing advice or services related to cannabis establishments or applications to
10 operate cannabis establishments on the basis that cannabis is illegal under federal law.
11 (b) An applicant for a professional or occupational license may not be denied a license
12 based on previous employment related to cannabis establishments operating in accordance with
13 State law.
14 "§ 18D-412. Private property and tenant rights.
15 (a) Except as provided in this section, the provisions of this Chapter do not require any
16 person, corporation, or any other entity that occupies, owns, or controls a property to allow the
17 consumption, cultivation, display, sale, or transfer of cannabis on or in that property.
18 (b) Except as provided in this section, a landlord or property manager may not refuse to
19 rent to a tenant, or otherwise discriminate against the tenant, based on a past conviction for a
20 cannabis offense.
21 (c) Except as provided in this section, in the case of the rental of a residential dwelling,
22 a landlord or property manager may not prohibit the possession of cannabis or the consumption
23 of cannabis by nonsmoked means.
24 (d) Subsections (a) through (c) of this section do not apply if any of the following
25 requirements are met:
26 (1) The tenant is not leasing the entire residential dwelling.
27 (2) The residence is incidental to detention or the provision of medical, geriatric,
28 educational, counseling, religious, or similar service.
29 (3) The residence is a transitional housing or sober living facility.
30 (4) Failing to prohibit cannabis possession or consumption would violate federal
31 law or regulations or cause the landlord to lose a monetary or licensing-related
32 benefit under federal law or regulations.
33 (e) After a warning, a landlord or property manager may take action against a tenant if
34 the tenant's use of cannabis creates an odor that interferes with others' peaceful enjoyment of
35 their home or property.
36 "§ 18D-413. Contracts enforceable.
37 It is the public policy of this State that contracts related to the operation of a cannabis
38 establishment registered pursuant to this Chapter should be enforceable. It is the public policy of
39 this State that no contract entered into by a cannabis establishment or its employees or agents as
40 permitted pursuant to a valid registration, or by those who allow property to be used by a cannabis
41 establishment, its employees, or its agents as permitted pursuant to a valid registration, shall be
42 unenforceable on the basis that cultivating, obtaining, manufacturing, distributing, dispensing,
43 transporting, selling, possessing, or using cannabis or hemp is prohibited by federal law.
44 "§ 18D-414. Respecting State law.
45 (a) No law enforcement officer employed by an agency that receives State or local
46 government funds shall expend any State or local resources, including the officer's time, to effect
47 any arrest or seizure of cannabis, or conduct any investigation, on the sole basis of activity the
48 officer believes to constitute a violation of federal law if the officer has reason to believe that
49 such activity is in compliance with this Chapter, nor shall any such officer expend any State or
50 local resources, including the officer's time, to provide any information or logistical support
51 related to such activity to any federal law enforcement authority or prosecuting entity.
Page 10 DRH10183-NLf-22

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b) No agency or political subdivision of the State may rely on a violation of federal law
2 related to cannabis as the sole basis for taking an adverse action against a person.
3 (c) For the purposes of State law, actions related to cannabis are considered lawful as
4 long as they are in accordance with this Chapter.
5 "§ 18D-415. Rulemaking.
6 (a) Not later than 180 days after the effective date of this Chapter, the Department shall
7 adopt rules necessary for implementation of this Chapter. Such rules shall not prohibit the
8 operation of cannabis establishments, either expressly or through application, nor require such a
9 high investment of risk, money, time, or any other resource or asset that the operation of a
10 cannabis establishment is not worthy of being carried out in practice by a reasonably prudent
11 businessperson. Such regulations shall include all of the following:
12 (1) Procedures for the issuance, renewal, suspension, and revocation of a
13 registration to operate a cannabis establishment, with such procedures subject
14 to all requirements of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
15 (2) Rules, procedures, and policies to promote and encourage full participation in
16 the regulated cannabis industry by people from communities that have
17 previously been disproportionately harmed by cannabis prohibition and
18 enforcement and to positively impact those communities, which shall reflect
19 input from the Office of Community Reinvestment, including all of the
20 following:
21 a. Conducting necessary and appropriate outreach to diverse groups that
22 may qualify for participation in activities under this Chapter.
23 b. Requiring each cannabis establishment to establish and adhere to
24 policies that encourage diversity in employment, contracting, and
25 other professional opportunities.
26 c. Requiring any cannabis establishment with 25 or more employees to
27 retain a diversity officer.
28 d. Requiring each cannabis establishment to report on the diversity of its
29 workforce, management, contracts, and ownership by January 1 of
30 each year.
31 e. Issuing rules allowing historically impacted applicants to apply for,
32 and be licensed for, cannabis establishment registrations no less than
33 180 days prior to applicants that are not historically impacted
34 applicants.
35 (3) A Race to the Top scoring system to make the expansion of a cannabis
36 establishment to more than two locations contingent on the cannabis
37 establishment's contributions to equity and to benefiting the community. The
38 system must reflect input from the Office of Community Reinvestment and
39 shall include, but need not be limited to, considerations of diversity in the
40 cannabis establishment's ownership and workforce, including in management;
41 employment of reentering citizens with prior convictions; minority
42 ownership; compensation packages and benefits for workers; investing in
43 economically disadvantaged areas; whether the cannabis establishment
44 incorporates principles of environmental resiliency or sustainability, including
45 energy efficiency; or whether the principals are historically impacted
46 applicants.
47 (4) A limit on the number of cannabis establishments a major investor may invest
48 in, unless each additional establishment is owned and operated by a
49 historically impacted applicant.
50 (5) A schedule of reasonable application, registration, and renewal fees, provided
51 application fees shall not exceed five thousand dollars ($5,000), with this
DRH10183-NLf-22 Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 upper limit adjusted annually for inflation, unless the Department determines
2 a greater fee is necessary to carry out its responsibilities under this Chapter.
3 (6) Qualifications for registration that are directly and demonstrably related to the
4 operation of a cannabis establishment and that may not disqualify applicants
5 solely for cannabis offenses prior to the effective date of this Chapter.
6 (7) Security requirements.
7 (8) Requirements for the transportation and storage of cannabis and cannabis
8 products by cannabis establishments.
9 (9) Requirements for the delivery of cannabis and cannabis products to
10 consumers, including a prohibition on business names, logos, and other
11 identifying language or images on delivery vehicles and a prohibition on
12 delivering to any address located on land owned by the federal government or
13 any address on land or in a building leased by the federal government.
14 (10) Employment and training requirements, including requiring that each
15 cannabis establishment create an identification badge for each employee or
16 agent. These requirements may not disqualify applicants solely for cannabis
17 offenses prior to the effective date of this Chapter.
18 (11) Requirements designed to prevent the sale or diversion of cannabis and
19 cannabis products to persons under the age of 21.
20 (12) Requirements for cannabis and cannabis products sold or distributed by a
21 cannabis establishment, including prohibiting any misleading labeling and
22 requiring cannabis product labels to include all of the following:
23 a. The length of time it typically takes for the product to take effect.
24 b. A disclosure of ingredients and possible allergens.
25 c. A nutritional fact panel.
26 d. Requiring opaque, child-resistant packaging, which must be designed
27 or constructed to be significantly difficult for children under 5 years
28 of age to open and not difficult for normal adults to use properly as
29 defined by 16 C.F.R. § 1700.20.
30 e. Requiring that edible cannabis products be clearly identifiable, when
31 practicable, with a standard symbol indicating that they contain
32 cannabis.
33 (13) Health and safety regulations and standards for the manufacture of cannabis
34 products and both the indoor and outdoor cultivation of cannabis by cannabis
35 establishments.
36 (14) Restrictions on advertising, marketing, and signage, including, but not limited
37 to, a prohibition on mass-market campaigns that have a high likelihood of
38 reaching minors.
39 (15) Rules to create at least six tiers of cannabis cultivation facilities, based on the
40 size of the facility or the number of plants cultivated and whether the
41 cultivation occurs outdoors, indoors, or in a greenhouse. Security regulations
42 and licensing fees must vary based on the size of the cultivation facility.
43 (16) Restrictions or prohibitions on additives to cannabis and cannabis-infused
44 products, including, but not limited to, those that are toxic or designed to make
45 the product more addictive.
46 (17) Prohibitions on products that are designed to make the product more appealing
47 to children, including prohibiting the use of any images designed or likely to
48 appeal to minors, including cartoons, toys, animals, or children, and any other
49 likeness to images, characters, or phrases that are popularly used to advertise
50 to children.
51 (18) Restrictions on the use of pesticides that are injurious to human health.
Page 12 DRH10183-NLf-22

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (19) Regulations governing visits to cannabis cultivation facilities and cannabis
2 product manufacturing facilities, including requiring the cannabis
3 establishment to log visitors.
4 (20) A definition of the amount of delta-9 tetrahydrocannabinol that constitutes a
5 single serving in a cannabis product.
6 (21) Standards for the safe manufacture of cannabis extracts and concentrates.
7 (22) Requirements that educational materials be disseminated to consumers who
8 purchase cannabis-infused products.
9 (23) Requirements for random sample testing to ensure quality control, including
10 by ensuring that cannabis and cannabis-infused products are accurately
11 labeled for potency. Unless the Department determines that remediation or
12 treatment is sufficient to ensure product safety, the testing analysis shall
13 include testing for residual solvents, poisons, or toxins; harmful chemicals;
14 dangerous molds or mildew; filth; and harmful microbials such as E. coli or
15 salmonella and pesticides.
16 (24) Standards for the operation of cannabis testing facilities, including
17 requirements for equipment and qualifications for personnel.
18 (25) Civil penalties for the failure to comply with rules made pursuant to this
19 Chapter.
20 (26) Procedures for collecting taxes levied on cannabis establishments.
21 (27) Requirements for on-site consumption establishments, including for security,
22 ventilation, odor control, and consumption by patrons. These rules may
23 include a prohibition on smoking indoors.
24 (b) After consulting with researchers knowledgeable about the risks and benefits of
25 cannabis and providing an opportunity for public comment, the Department shall develop a
26 scientifically accurate safety information label, handout, or both, which shall be available to each
27 adult-use cannabis consumer. The label or handout shall include both of the following:
28 (1) Advice about the potential risks of cannabis, including all of the following:
29 a. The risks of driving under the influence of cannabis and the fact that
30 doing so is illegal.
31 b. Any adverse effects unique to younger adults, including related to the
32 developing mind.
33 c. Potential adverse events and other risks.
34 d. Risks of using cannabis during pregnancy or breastfeeding.
35 (2) The need to safeguard all cannabis and cannabis products from children and
36 pets.
37 (c) The Department shall review and update the safety information materials at least once
38 every two years to ensure they remain accurate. The review period shall include soliciting input
39 from researchers knowledgeable about the risks and benefits of cannabis and an opportunity for
40 public comment.
41 (d) In order to ensure that individual privacy is protected, the Department shall not require
42 a consumer to provide a retail cannabis store with personal information other than
43 government-issued identification to determine the consumer's age and a retail cannabis store shall
44 not be required to acquire and record personal information about consumers.
45 "Article 5.
46 "Taxes and Use of Revenue.
47 "§ 18D-500. Cannabis Regulation Fund.
48 The Cannabis Regulation Fund is established in the Department. The Fund shall consist of
49 fees collected under this Chapter and appropriations made by the General Assembly to the Fund.
50 The Department shall administer the Fund, and funds in the Fund are hereby appropriated for the
51 purposes set forth in this Article.
DRH10183-NLf-22 Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 18D-501. Cannabis excise tax.
2 (a) There is imposed a cannabis excise tax equal to thirty percent (30%) of the sales price
3 of each sale of cannabis and cannabis products to a consumer. Sales to registered medical
4 cannabis patients pursuant to applicable law are exempt from the tax imposed under this section.
5 (b) The tax imposed by this section shall be paid by the consumer to the cannabis
6 establishment. Each cannabis establishment shall collect from the consumer the full amount of
7 the tax payable on each taxable sale.
8 (c) On the fifteenth day of each month, every cannabis establishment that sells cannabis
9 to consumers shall pay the excise taxes due on the cannabis that the cannabis establishment sold
10 in the prior calendar month.
11 (d) The cannabis excise tax shall be separately itemized from the cannabis excise tax on
12 the receipt provided to the purchaser.
13 "§ 18D-502. Cannabis local option tax.
14 (a) Any municipality may collect a cannabis local option tax of two percent (2%) of the
15 sales price on each sale of cannabis and cannabis products to a consumer in the municipality.
16 Sales to registered medical cannabis patients pursuant to applicable law are exempt from the tax
17 imposed under this section.
18 (b) The cannabis local option tax may be adopted by a municipality that has provided (i)
19 notice of the imposition and (ii) the amount to the Department of Revenue at least 90 days prior
20 to the first day of the tax quarter when the cannabis local option tax will be collected.
21 (c) The tax imposed by this section shall be paid by the consumer to the cannabis
22 establishment. Each cannabis establishment shall collect from the consumer the full amount of
23 the tax payable on each taxable sale.
24 (d) On the fifteenth day of each month, every cannabis establishment that sells cannabis
25 to consumers shall pay the local option taxes due on the cannabis that the cannabis establishment
26 sold in the prior calendar month.
27 (e) The tax imposed by this section is separate from and in addition to the cannabis excise
28 tax authorized under G.S. 18D-501. The tax imposed by this section shall not be part of the sales
29 price to which the cannabis excise tax applies. The cannabis local option tax shall be separately
30 itemized from the cannabis excise tax on the receipt provided to the purchaser.
31 "§ 18D-503. Apportionment of revenue.
32 Revenues generated in excess of the amount needed to implement and enforce this Chapter
33 by the cannabis excise tax shall be distributed every three months as follows:
34 (1) Twenty-five percent (25%) shall be distributed to the Community
35 Reinvestment and Repair Fund established by this Chapter.
36 (2) Ten percent (10%) shall be distributed to the Cannabis Enterprise Opportunity
37 Fund established by this Chapter.
38 (3) Three percent (3%) shall be distributed to the Cannabis Education and
39 Technical Assistance Fund established by this Chapter.
40 (4) Seven percent (7%) shall be distributed to the Department of Health and
41 Human Services for use in evidence-based, voluntary programs for the
42 prevention or treatment of substance abuse.
43 (5) Two percent (2%) shall be distributed to the Department of Health and Human
44 Services for a scientifically and medically accurate public education campaign
45 educating youth and adults about the health and safety risks of alcohol,
46 tobacco, cannabis, and other substances, including the risks of driving while
47 impaired.
48 (6) Two percent (2%) shall be distributed to the Department of Health and Human
49 Services to fund diverse scientific, academic, or medical research on cannabis
50 or endocannabinoids, including research exploring the benefits of cannabis,
51 provided that all funded research data, results, and papers shall be released
Page 14 DRH10183-NLf-22

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 into the public domain and shall be published for free and open access by the
2 public and by other researchers.
3 (7) Up to one percent (1%) shall be distributed to the Department of Public Safety
4 to fund Advanced Roadside Impaired Driving Enforcement and drug
5 recognition expert training.
6 (8) Any remaining funds shall be deposited in the General Fund."
